Subject: Advisory Panel on Offshore Energy

Comment: As a member of the coastal wind working group I was sent a copy of the slides presented at the Buxton offshore wind meeting the other week. I was a little disappointed that the consultants in charge of the offshore platforms section of the report omitted a long-proven method of supporting equipment in an offshore environment. It is also the least expensive. I contacted Harvey Seim who presented the slides at the Buxton meeting so he could comment for the panel. See below. Re: Offshore Platforms Tuesday, September 29, 2009 1:39 AM From: "Harvey Seim" To: "Robert Getchell" "You are correct, the Dutch firm who suggested appropriate foundation designs did not consider this one. Thanks for pointing it out." Harvey Titan 200 Offshore Wind Platform This platform can be set up in depths of up to 200 feet, without the use of pilings or jack-up barges. The oil industry has been using the Titan 200 Platform in offshore oil fields for decades. Recently one of the original designers, Doug Hines of Offshore Wind Platforms of Texas, modified the design for wind turbine applications. A major advantage is all assembly takes place in port. When the three deck platform is towed out of port, with a turbine already erected on the top deck, it is a registered vessel. Once in place the three legs are lowered to the bottom, ballast tanks are filled, the footings settle 8-12 feet into the bottom, and are then covered with concrete matting for scour protection. Once leveled the platform is jacked up 60 feet above the ocean surface. J-tubes in the legs carry cable from the seabed to the switching disconnects and other equipment inside the platform. The Titan platforms survived the category 5 winds of Katrina a few years ago, with no damage. MMS has certified the design for offshore use in US waters. Using a platform is cheaper than a piling, and environmental impacts from construction, assembly and decommissioning are virtually eliminated. For an additional cost, decks can be retrofitted to carry additional equipment, house crew and there is also a desalinization system that is made for the Titan 200 platform. We looked at Cape Winds proposal, talked to a lot of the designers and environmental consultants who worked on the project, even met with Doug Hines in DC where he had been called to speak before a congressional panel about these wind platforms. Any offshore project we pursue will use the Titan 200 Wind Platform. We are focusing on acquisition of Frying Pan Shoals tower to get an offshore site in a prime wind location. If USACE will allow us to turn the old tower into an artificial reef we'll replace the old tower with a new Titan 200 on the same lease site. I encourage you to google up Offshore Wind Platforms of Texas. I'm sure Doug can answer any questions you or anyone else may have. There is also some cost comparison information on the site that is useful. Sincerely, Bob Getchell Noreaster Energy Partners

