Comment: Harold Marvin 1010 Atando Ave Charlotte, NC 28206-2251 October 23, 2009 The Honorable Beverly Perdue Governor of North Carolina 20301 Mail Service Center Raleigh, NC 27699-0301 Dear Governor Perdue: I am writing to urge you to work with your colleagues to enact legislation that will assist the construction equipment industry recover from the terrible economic situation the industry is currently facing. While other sectors of the U.S. economy appear to be recovering from the recession, the construction equipment industry remains mired in a deep depression. On September 29, the Associated Equipment Distributors (AED) and the Associated Equipment Manufacturers (AEM) released the results of an equipment industry economic condition. Among the key findings: � The construction equipment industry - which includes manufacturing, distribution and maintenance companies - has shed a staggering 37 percent of its workforce since the equipment market peaked in 2006. By comparison, auto manufacturing and dealership jobs are down by 16 percent, while job losses in the finance and insurance industry amount to 6 percent of their workforce. � Spending on construction equipment has fallen by more than 50 percent compared to its peak in 2006. � The economic output of this industry has contracted by nearly 40 percent and resulted, directly and indirectly, in the loss of approximately 550,000 jobs. In other words, eight percent of all jobs lost since the start the recession have been associated with the equipment industry downturn. � Over the course of the recession, losses to industry sales and employment have decimated the taxes paid on employee income, corporate profits and sales of machinery; the magnitude of the decline indicates that taxes revenues associated with our industry have fallen by $12.8 billion. Without significant congressional action, the construction industry economic crisis will continue for the foreseeable future and prevent recovery in the broader economy. In order to assist the construction equipment industry recover from the depression it is in, I urge Congress to quickly pursue the following legislative initiatives to create new construction industry jobs and revitalize the construction equipment industry. � Invest in critical infrastructure by swiftly passing multi-year reauthorization bills that increase investment in the nation's highways, public transportation, bridges, sewers, drinking water systems, and airports. To pay for investment in the highway program, Congress should support a user fee increase, the fairest and most fiscally responsible way to pay for additional revenue. Many leading business groups support a user fee increase, including AED, AEM, AAA, the American Trucking Associations, the National Association of Manufacturers, and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. � Ensure that credit is available to equipment distributors, manufacturers, purchasers, and to developers. The construction industry is facing an unprecedented credit crisis. Congress and the executive branch must work together to put programs in place to ensure that dealers and manufacturers have access to capital to run their companies, that customers can get credit to buy equipment, and that developers can access the money they need to undertake new construction projects. � Extend and expand the home purchase tax credit. � Extend the stimulus bill's capital investment incentives and create new tax credits to encourage "clean diesel" equipment purchases. � Extend and expand net operating loss (NOL) carry back rules. Congress should allow 2009 losses to be carried back for five years and significantly raise the eligibility cap for companies to take advantage of NOL carry-back benefits. I urge you to strongly consider the aforementioned proposals. Thank you for your consideration. Sincerely, H.W. Marvin III 7043330786

